node.text:
“We need to understand the difference between normal and common. ⁠
⁠
It is not normal to be traumatized by birth. However, an estimated 30-40% of mothers describe their births as “traumatic”, even when both the mother and the baby survive. It is common... but not normal. I am here to tell you that your anger and pain surrounding your birth trauma are valid, and you are not alone.⁠
⁠
⁠This is a problem. It is unacceptable to normalize obstetric abuse under the convenient, neutral guise of “birth trauma”. It is unacceptable that the harm done to women in the name of health has been so normalized that 1/3 of mothers have been violated, controlled, and traumatized, and there is no widespread outrage. It is unacceptable that fear is used as a weapon to keep us trauma-bonded to the system. It is unacceptable that women have been silenced by a culture that buys into the God complex found in modern industrialized medicine. It is unacceptable to feed women the lie that trauma is a rite of passage to motherhood.⁠
⁠
. ⁠Routine hospital birth exists to fix problems it creates. 1% of American births take place outside of a hospital. So why do we have arguably the worst outcome stats in the developed world? If there is a negative outcome at a homebirth, all we hear is, “Why weren’t you in the hospital? Don’t you know the risks?” But when there is a negative outcome at the hospital (which is not limited to maternal or infant mortality, btw), nobody says, “Why did you go to the hospital? Why didn’t you just stay home? Don’t you know the risks of hospital birth?” No. We never hear that. Because we have been made to believe that medicalized birth is safe and undisturbed physiologic birth is not. And this is a lie.”⁠
⁠
.⁠Some birth trauma is unavoidable. Sometimes, bad things just happen. But do these bad things “just” happen to 1/3 of mothers? Or are there tools in place which sabotage natural birth? Is it possible that there are systems that operate like a well-oiled machine, working against birth instead of for it? Is it conceivable that what our culture believes about birth has been fabricated? Is it possible that trauma is not normal?⁠
⁠
@nicki.french⁠

node.text:
“Long term impacts of the NICU... ⁠
⁠
We are aware that everyone's experiences are different, however there seem to be common themes that a lot of people tend to live through, so we want to talk about them.⁠
⁠
The rate of mental health problems after a NICU experience for parents is higher than it is in other new parents, the level of trauma experienced is extremely high, and yet this is a group of people who have very limited support and are often silenced, often not intentionally, but through lack of understanding from others who have not been through it and don’t know what a NICU experience can really be like.⁠
⁠
So, feel free to interact, let us know what your feelings and thoughts are about these areas and let's drop the narrative that the impact of the NICU stops as soon as we get home from hospital. ⁠
⁠
It is often something that we are never “over”, but we live with, it becomes part of our story. “⁠
⁠
@miraclemoonuk⁠
⁠

node.text:
⁠"We’re encouraged as moms to take a hot shower or go to the grocery store alone...as if these “luxuries” will have long lasting effects on our mental health. Now don’t get me wrong, they’re nice, but they aren’t the cure for burnout.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Burnout is more than a "you" problem, it’s a system problem. Our current demands far outweigh our capabilities. We’re being asked to do the impossible and we’re left feeling inadequate when falling short.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Some things can change right now. We can:⁠⁠
⁠⁠
1. Share responsibilities when possible⁠⁠
⁠
2. Do the “bare minimum” or “just enough.” These are hard times and no one is passing out gold stars, I promise.⁠⁠
⁠
3. Take breaks when possible. Sometimes this takes creativity. This can mean using technology, toddler activities, asking your support person, neighbor, etc.⁠⁠
⁠
4. Be mindful of your self-talk and stop putting yourself down ⁠⁠
⁠
5. Ask for help. Therapy is an incredible tool that can help you feel better⁠⁠
⁠⁠
⁠
What’s something that you do to combat burnout?⁠⁠"⁠
⁠
- @psychedmommy⁠
⁠
⁠
[IMAGE ID: infographic with Light lavender background and a woman with black hair resting her head in her hand. Text reads : Taking an uninterrupted shower will not cure burnout. What you really need to do: Delegate some of the responsibilities that can be shared. Give yourself permission to do "just enough". Know that it is okay to seek professional help. Be kind to yourself (stop putting yourself down). Take breaks]
